<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Extended Memory Specification" class="currentChild" href="Extended_Memory_Specification">Extended Memory Specification</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In computers, especially those running the <a title="MS-DOS" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/MS-DOS">MS-DOS</a> operating system, a successor to the <a title="expanded memory specification" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/expanded_memory_specification">expanded memory specification</a> that allowed 80X86 computers to access additional memory, both for storage and for running applications. XMS required a 16-<a title="Bit" href="Bit">bit</a> processor, but with the advent of 32-Bit processors all extended and expanded memory features are available directly within the <a title="microprocessor" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/microprocessor">microprocessor</a>. 
</p>
